Mathematical and Architectural Foundations for Hand Finger Movement Analysis: A Unified Framework Integrating Geometric Mechanics with Spatial Design Principles

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Date: 20

---

Abstract

The human hand represents one of the most sophisticated biomechanical systems, yet current approaches to understanding and replicating its movements remain fragmented between mathematical modeling and physical design. This dissertation develops a unified theoretical framework that integrates advanced mathematical modeling with architectural and design principles to analyze, represent, and generate hand finger movements. By synthesizing geometric mechanics—including screw theory, Lie groups, and port-Hamiltonian systems—with spatial design thinking drawn from architecture, the work establishes a novel interdisciplinary language for describing hand kinematics and dynamics. The framework introduces formal spatial grammars for hand movements, pattern languages for grasping, and tectonic principles for mechanical expression, while maintaining rigorous mathematical foundations. Building upon prior work in port-Hamiltonian finger modeling and screw-theoretic hand analysis, this dissertation provides the first unified integration of geometric mechanics with human-centered spatial design principles. The coupling–adaptation paradox is characterized geometrically through a novel adaptation index, and formal mappings between mathematical and design representations enable dual representation and integrated design space exploration. A theoretical design exploration illustrates Pareto-optimal trade-offs between functional adaptation and mechanical legibility. This integration bridges the gap between mathematical abstraction and human‑centered design, offering a theoretical basis for applications in prosthetics, rehabilitation, and human‑robot interaction.

Keywords: Hand kinematics, geometric mechanics, screw theory, Lie groups, port-Hamiltonian systems, architectural design, spatial grammars, pattern languages, tectonics, underactuation, coupling–adaptation paradox, mechanical legibility, computational design.

