Chapter 2: Literature Review

2.1 Mathematical Foundations of Kinematic and Dynamic Modeling

2.1.1 Classical Formulations: Denavit–Hartenberg and Lagrangian Mechanics

The mathematical study of robotic manipulators began with classical approaches rooted in vector mechanics. The Denavit–Hartenberg (DH) convention (Denavit & Hartenberg 1955) provides a systematic method for describing serial chain manipulators using four parameters per joint. For a finger with n joints, the forward kinematics are expressed as a product of homogeneous transformation matrices. While widely used, DH parameters have limitations: they become singular for certain joint configurations and obscure the underlying geometric structure.

Lagrangian dynamics provide the natural extension to motion analysis. For a finger with generalized coordinates q, the equations of motion derive from the Lagrangian L = K - V. Applied to finger segments modeled as coupled pendula, this yields equations representing inertia, damping, and stiffness contributions—the so‑called IBK model.

2.1.2 Geometric Approaches: Screw Theory and Lie Groups

The limitations of classical formulations motivated the development of geometric methods rooted in differential geometry and Lie group theory. Murray, Li, and Sastry (1994) established screw theory and the product of exponentials (POE) as fundamental tools. In the POE formulation, the forward kinematics of an n-joint manipulator are expressed as a product of matrix exponentials of screw axes, starting from a home configuration. This formulation offers several advantages: it avoids singularities, handles revolute and prismatic joints uniformly, and reveals the group structure of rigid motions.

Screw-Theoretic Hand Analysis: Dai (2009) applied screw theory to the metamorphic multifingered Metahand, analyzing workspace and orientation capabilities via screw systems and SE(3) geometry. More recent extensions include compliant grippers (Borràs & Dollar 2014), articulation estimation through ScrewNet (2023), and hybrid rigid-continuum mechanisms.

The configuration space of a manipulator is a Lie group—typically SE(3) or one of its subgroups. This geometric perspective enables powerful tools from differential geometry, such as the exponential map and Lie algebra, to be applied to kinematic analysis, and it naturally accommodates the study of symmetries and invariants.

2.1.3 Port‑Hamiltonian Systems for Energy‑Aware Dynamics

Port‑Hamiltonian systems, developed by van der Schaft and Maschke (2002), extend geometric mechanics to incorporate energy exchange with the environment. A port‑Hamiltonian system is defined on a state manifold X with Hamiltonian H: X → ℝ representing total stored energy. The dynamics are structured with a skew‑symmetric interconnection matrix J(x), a dissipation matrix R(x) ≥ 0, and power‑conjugate port variables (u, y).

Port-Hamiltonian Applications to Robotic Fingers: Wassink, Carloni, and Stramigioli (2010) modeled a novel underactuated variable-impedance finger with antagonistic tendons, series-elastic springs, and joint locks using port-Hamiltonian systems on Dirac structures. Their state vector included momenta, joint angles, and spring elongations, with Hamiltonian incorporating kinetic and elastic energy. The interconnection structure included an actuation Jacobian related to screw-based geometric Jacobians for twists and wrenches. Crucially, they explicitly handled underactuation through the kernel of the actuation matrix and demonstrated how compliance tuning affects grasp performance.

Ficuciello et al. (2010) extended this approach to multi-fingered hands with soft finger pads, incorporating contact models and showing how port-Hamiltonian formulations preserve passivity during manipulation. Recent work (Finzi et al. 2023) has added neural port-Hamiltonian ODEs on Lie groups, and rehabilitation applications with electromyographic control integration continue to emerge.

This formulation is ideal for hand modeling because it explicitly represents energy flows, preserves passivity ensuring stable interaction with uncertain environments, allows modular composition of subsystems (fingers, tendons, actuators), and naturally accommodates underactuation and variable transmission.

2.1.4 Tendon‑Driven Mechanism Theory

Tendon‑driven systems are ubiquitous in hand design due to their anthropomorphic inspiration and ability to locate actuators remotely. The mathematical theory addresses several unique aspects:

Tendon Routing and Coupling Matrix: For a finger with n joints and m tendons, the relationship between tendon displacements Δl and joint angles Δθ is Δl = P Δθ, where P is the coupling matrix. The rank of P determines the degree of underactuation.

Force Transmission: By the principle of virtual work, joint torques τ relate to tendon tensions f via τ = Pᵀ f.

Variable Transmission: For some designs, P varies with joint configuration due to changing moment arms or tendon wrapping. This configuration-dependence can be exploited to achieve different coupling ratios at different grasp phases (Birglen et al. 2008).

Friction and Hysteresis: Tendon friction introduces nonlinear, history‑dependent behavior. Common models include the Dahl model and the LuGre model (Canudas de Wit et al. 1995), which capture the gradual transition between static and kinetic friction regimes.

2.2 Hand Biomechanics and Underactuation

2.2.1 Kinematic Structure of the Human Hand

The human hand consists of 27 bones, including 8 carpals, 5 metacarpals, and 14 phalanges. The fingers (index, middle, ring, little) each have three phalanges (proximal, middle, distal) and three joints: metacarpophalangeal (MCP), proximal interphalangeal (PIP), and distal interphalangeal (DIP). The thumb has two phalanges and two joints: MCP and interphalangeal (IP), plus a carpometacarpal (CMC) joint that enables opposition.

Degrees of freedom vary across joints: MCP joints provide flexion/extension and abduction/adduction (2 DoF), while PIP and DIP joints provide only flexion/extension (1 DoF each). The thumb CMC is a saddle joint with 2–3 DoF. Total DoF ranges from 21 to 27 depending on modeling choices.

2.2.2 Underactuated Finger Mechanisms

Underactuation—using fewer actuators than degrees of freedom—has emerged as a key principle for achieving adaptability with minimal complexity. Underactuated fingers automatically conform to object shape through passive compliance. The fundamental architecture uses a single actuator to drive multiple joints via a mechanism that distributes motion.

Comprehensive Treatment: Birglen, Gosselin, and Laliberté (2008) provided the foundational text Underactuated Robotic Hands, systematically analyzing various linkage and tendon-driven architectures. Dollar and Howe (2010) investigated the role of joint coupling in adaptive grasping, demonstrating how coupling ratios affect the speed and reliability of grasp formation. The RBO SoftHand (Deimel & Brock 2016) and Robotiq adaptive grippers represent successful commercial implementations.

The coupling matrix P determines how actuator displacement distributes among joints. For a two‑joint finger, typical coupling is P = [1; k], meaning that for a unit actuator displacement, the proximal joint moves by 1 unit and the distal joint by k units.

2.2.3 The Coupling–Adaptation Paradox

A fundamental trade‑off in underactuated fingers is between joint coupling (all joints moving simultaneously) and shape adaptation (joints stopping sequentially upon contact). High coupling (k near 1) gives simultaneous motion but poor adaptation; low coupling (k ≪ 1) gives sequential motion (good adaptation) but slow grasp formation.

Recent patents (e.g., Gosselin & Laliberté 2014, US Patent 8,870,269) discuss "coupled-adaptive" mode-switching mechanisms that attempt to resolve this paradox through variable transmission or differential mechanisms. However, a rigorous geometric characterization has been lacking—a gap this dissertation addresses through the introduction of an adaptation index.

2.3 Architectural and Design Thinking

2.3.1 Adaptability in Architecture

Architecture has long grappled with designing for change. Brand (1994) identified six layers of building adaptation, each with different timescales: site (eternal), structure (30–300 years), skin (20 years), services (7–15 years), space plan (3–30 years), and stuff (daily). This layering suggests that adaptability requires designing at multiple timescales simultaneously—a principle directly applicable to hand design, where kinematic structure, actuation, sensing, and control operate on different timescales.

Hertzberger (2005) concept of polyvalence—designing elements that accommodate multiple uses without physical change—offers another key insight. A well‑designed underactuated finger is polyvalent: it adapts to different object shapes without active reconfiguration.

2.3.2 Tectonics and Mechanical Legibility

Tectonics, as developed by Frampton (2007), refers to the expressive potential of constructional logic—the way structural principles become visible and meaningful in the finished work. Applied to hand design, tectonics suggests that the mechanical logic of actuation and transmission should be expressed rather than concealed.

While "tectonics" specifically has not been applied to prosthetic design, adjacent fields such as expressive robotics (Hoffman 2013) and legible robot motion (Dragan et al. 2013) have explored how form and motion communicate intent. We extend these ideas by proposing that a tectonically designed hand is mechanically legible—its form reveals its function, reducing cognitive load for the user and potentially increasing trust. This reframes tectonic qualities from mere aesthetics to cognitive ergonomics.

2.3.3 Pattern Languages and Spatial Grammars

Alexander's (1977) pattern language provides a method for codifying design knowledge at multiple scales. Each pattern describes a recurring problem and its core solution, expressed in a form that allows combination with other patterns. Applied to manipulation, a pattern language would capture recurring grasp types, finger configurations, and movement sequences.

No prior application of Alexander's pattern language exists in the hand design literature. Kinematic synergies (Santello et al. 1998) capture similar ideas mathematically but lack the contextual documentation and design guidance that patterns provide.

Spatial grammars—rule‑based systems for generating spatial configurations—offer a complementary formalism. A spatial grammar for hand movements would consist of primitives (fundamental movement elements), rules (ways of combining primitives), and constraints (conditions for valid configurations).

2.4 Identified Research Gaps

The literature review reveals several gaps that this dissertation addresses:

1. Unified Integration of Existing Mathematical Frameworks: While screw theory and port‑Hamiltonian systems have been applied individually to manipulators and fingers (Wassink et al. 2010; Dai 2009), no existing work integrates them into a comprehensive framework for hand modeling that also incorporates design-oriented representations.
2. Formal Characterization of the Coupling–Adaptation Trade-off: The coupling–adaptation paradox lacks a rigorous mathematical formulation that could guide mechanism design and optimization.
3. Design‑Oriented Representations: Despite the obvious parallels between hand design and architecture, no systematic effort has applied architectural theories—pattern languages, spatial grammars, tectonics—to hand movement analysis.
4. Integration of Mathematics and Design: There is no formal methodology for translating between mathematical descriptions (joint angles, forces) and design representations (patterns, grammars), limiting the ability to combine analytical rigor with human‑centered creativity.
5. Theoretical Design Tools for Hand Mechanisms: Existing design tools for robotic hands are either purely analytical or purely empirical. A theoretical framework that unifies functional metrics (like adaptation) with human-centered metrics (like legibility) is lacking.

