Chapter 3: Geometric Framework for Hand Modeling

3.1 Mathematical Preliminaries

3.1.1 Lie Groups and the Special Euclidean Group SE(3)

The set of all rigid body motions in three‑dimensional space forms the special Euclidean group SE(3). An element of SE(3) can be represented as a pair (R, p) where R ∈ SO(3) is a rotation matrix and p ∈ ℝ³ is a translation vector. Group multiplication is (R₁, p₁)·(R₂, p₂) = (R₁R₂, R₁p₂ + p₁).

SE(3) is a six‑dimensional Lie group. Its Lie algebra se(3) consists of twists ξ = (v, ω) where v ∈ ℝ³ is linear velocity and ω ∈ ℝ³ is angular velocity. The exponential map exp: se(3) → SE(3) converts twists to rigid motions. For a twist ξ = (v, ω) with θ = ‖ω‖, the exponential is given by the Rodrigues formula. For the special case ω = 0 (pure translation), exp(ξ̂) = (I, v).

3.1.2 Screw Theory and the Product of Exponentials

A screw is a geometric entity comprising a line in space (the screw axis) and a pitch. The instantaneous motion of a rigid body can be represented as a twist—the velocity analogue of a screw. For a revolute joint with axis ω (unit vector) and point q on the axis, the screw axis is S = [-ω×q; ω]. For a prismatic joint with direction v, the screw axis is S = [v; 0].

The product of exponentials formula expresses the forward kinematics of an n-joint manipulator as T(θ) = exp([S₁]θ₁) exp([S₂]θ₂) … exp([S_n]θ_n) M, where [S_i] is the 4×4 matrix representation of the screw axis, and M is the home configuration.

3.1.3 Port‑Hamiltonian Systems on Manifolds

A port‑Hamiltonian system is defined on a manifold X with Hamiltonian H: X → ℝ. The dynamics are ẋ = [J(x) - R(x)] (∂H/∂x)(x) + g(x)u, y = gᵀ(x) (∂H/∂x)(x), with J(x) skew‑symmetric, R(x) ≥ 0, and (u, y) power‑conjugate ports. This formulation preserves the geometric structure and energy properties of the system.

Following Wassink et al. (2010), we extend this to tendon-driven fingers by including tendon elongation states ℓ and elastic elements: x = [q; p; ℓ], H(q,p,ℓ) = ½ pᵀ M⁻¹(q) p + V(q) + ½ ℓᵀ K_e ℓ, where K_e represents tendon elasticity, M(q) is the inertia matrix, and V(q) includes gravitational and elastic potential energy.

3.2 Kinematic Modeling via Product of Exponentials

3.2.1 Finger as an Open Kinematic Chain

Consider a finger with n joints. Let the base frame be attached to the palm, and let M ∈ SE(3) be the fingertip pose when all joint angles are zero. For each joint i, define a screw axis S_i expressed in the base frame. The forward kinematics are T(θ) = exp([S₁]θ₁) exp([S₂]θ₂) … exp([S_n]θ_n) M.

For a typical finger, joints alternate between flexion/extension axes (perpendicular to finger plane) and abduction/adduction axes (orthogonal to flexion axes). The screw axes reflect this geometry.

3.2.2 Incorporating Multiple Fingers and the Thumb

A full hand model consists of five fingers, each described by its own product of exponentials. The thumb requires special attention due to its opposable saddle joint, which can be modeled as two intersecting revolute axes following Dai's (2009) screw-based thumb representation.

Let T_f(θ_f) denote the fingertip pose of finger f as a function of its joint angles θ_f. The overall hand configuration is the tuple (θ₁, …, θ₅).

3.2.3 Configuration Space and Its Topology

The configuration space of a single finger is a product of circles (for revolute joints) and lines (for prismatic joints), i.e., an n-dimensional torus Tⁿ if all joints are revolute. For the whole hand, the configuration space is the product of the individual finger spaces: C = Tⁿ¹ × Tⁿ² × … × Tⁿ⁵. This space has the topology of a high‑dimensional torus. Understanding its geometry is essential for analyzing hand movements and planning motions.

3.3 Dynamic Modeling with Port‑Hamiltonian Systems

3.3.1 Hamiltonian Formulation for Multi‑Segment Fingers

For a finger with n segments, choose generalized coordinates q ∈ ℝⁿ (joint angles) and generalized momenta p = M(q) q̇, where M(q) is the inertia matrix. The Hamiltonian is H(q, p) = ½ pᵀ M⁻¹(q) p + V(q), where V(q) includes gravitational and elastic potential energy.

The port‑Hamiltonian dynamics are:
[ q̇; ṗ ] = ( [0 I; -I 0] - [0 0; 0 R(q,p)] ) [∂H/∂q; ∂H/∂p] + [0; B(q)] u,
y = Bᵀ(q) ∂H/∂p = Bᵀ(q) M⁻¹(q) p.

3.3.2 Tendon Transmission and the Coupling Matrix

The input matrix B(q) maps tendon forces u to joint torques. For a tendon‑driven finger with m tendons, the relationship is τ = Pᵀ(q) f, where P(q) is the coupling matrix. Following Wassink et al. (2010), the coupling matrix relates to the geometric Jacobian J(q) through Pᵀ(q) = J_aᵀ(q) J_tendon(q), where J_a captures actuator coupling and J_tendon maps tendon velocities to joint velocities. For constant tendon moment arms, P is constant; for designs with wrapping or variable-radius pulleys, P(q) becomes configuration-dependent—a feature that can be exploited to achieve variable coupling ratios.

3.3.3 Dissipation and Friction Modeling

Dissipation R(q, p) captures friction at joints and along tendons. A common model is Rayleigh dissipation: R(q, p) = [0 0; 0 D(q, q̇)], where D(q, q̇) is a positive definite matrix representing joint damping and tendon friction. For tendon friction, the LuGre model (Canudas de Wit et al. 1995) can be incorporated by augmenting the state with internal friction states z: ż = ℓ̇ - σ₀ |ℓ̇|/g(ℓ̇) z, F_fric = σ₀ z + σ₁ ż + σ₂ ℓ̇, where σ₀, σ₁, σ₂ are friction parameters and g(ℓ̇) captures the Stribeck effect.

3.4 Underactuation and the Coupling–Adaptation Paradox

3.4.1 Mathematical Characterization of Underactuated Fingers

An underactuated finger has fewer actuators than degrees of freedom: m < n. The dynamics become τ = Pᵀ f, with rank(P) = m. The nullspace of Pᵀ represents directions in torque space that cannot be directly actuated. These directions are governed by passive elements (springs, mechanical limits) and contact forces.

Following Wassink et al. (2010), we represent the underactuated dynamics as ẋ = [J(x) - R(x)] (∂H/∂x)(x) + g(x)u + g_c(x)λ, where g_c(x)λ represents contact forces and λ are Lagrange multipliers enforcing contact constraints.

3.4.2 The Adaptation Index: Quantifying the Paradox

We introduce a geometric metric to quantify the coupling–adaptation trade-off. Let P ∈ ℝⁿᵐ be the coupling matrix.

Definition (Adaptation Index): The adaptation index of an underactuated finger with coupling matrix P is AI(P) = dim(ker(Pᵀ)) / rank(P).

For an n×m matrix with rank r, dim(ker(Pᵀ)) = n - r, so AI(P) = (n - r) / r.

This index measures the dimension of the subspace of joint torques that cannot be directly actuated, normalized by the number of actuated degrees of freedom. A fully actuated finger (r = n) has AI = 0, indicating no passive adaptation capability. A minimally underactuated finger (r = 1) has AI = n-1, indicating maximum potential for adaptation but minimal coordinated motion.

Remarks: The adaptation index depends only on the rank of P, not on the specific values within P. While this coarse measure captures the fundamental capacity for passive adaptation (the size of the nullspace), it does not reflect how the passive subspace is oriented relative to joint stiffness or contact geometries. For a more detailed analysis, complementary metrics are needed. In particular, we define the condition number of P as κ(P) = σ_max(P) / σ_min(P), where σ_max and σ_min are the largest and smallest singular values of P. This ratio captures the uniformity of coupling: a high condition number indicates that some actuated directions are much more effective than others, which can affect the finger's ability to transmit forces evenly. Two coupling matrices with the same rank but different κ can have markedly different mechanical behavior. For example, P₁ = [1, 1; 0.1, 0.1]ᵀ and P₂ = [1, 0.1; 0.1, 1]ᵀ both have rank 2 but very different condition numbers, leading to different force transmission characteristics. Thus AI serves as a first-order characterization, sufficient for comparing mechanisms with different degrees of underactuation, while κ provides additional insight when comparing mechanisms with the same rank but different coupling structures.

Definition (Coupling Index): The coupling index measures how well the actuated motions align with a desired grasp synergy vector c ∈ ℝⁿ: CI(P, c) = ‖P P⁺ c‖ / ‖c‖, where P⁺ is the pseudoinverse of P. CI = 1 indicates that c lies entirely in the column space of P (perfect coupling); CI = 0 indicates c is orthogonal to the actuated subspace.

3.4.3 Distinction from Classical Manipulability

While Yoshikawa's (1985) manipulability ellipsoid √det(JJᵀ) quantifies the ability to generate velocity in task space, the adaptation index quantifies the structural capacity for passive conformation. Manipulability is about active control authority; AI is about passive mechanical intelligence. A finger can have high AI (good adaptation) but low manipulability (poor force transmission) if the coupling matrix is ill-conditioned. This distinction is crucial for design.

The coupling–adaptation paradox can now be stated geometrically:

Theorem (Paradox as Geometric Constraint): For any constant coupling matrix P, there exists a fundamental trade-off between adaptation and coupling. Specifically, for any desired synergy vector c, the product AI(P) · CI(P, c) is bounded above by a function of the condition number of P and the alignment of c with the column space. High AI (large nullspace) necessarily limits the ability to achieve arbitrary coupled motions, and vice versa. The condition number amplifies the trade-off when P is ill-conditioned.

Proof Sketch: Let P have singular value decomposition P = U Σ Vᵀ, with Σ = diag(σ₁,…,σ_m) and σ₁ ≥ … ≥ σ_m > 0. Then rank(P) = m, and dim(ker(Pᵀ)) = n - m. Thus AI = (n-m)/m. For any unit vector c, the projection onto the column space is P P⁺ c = U Ũᵀ c, where Ũ consists of the first m columns of U. The norm ‖P P⁺ c‖ is maximized when c lies in the subspace spanned by the first m left singular vectors, and minimized when orthogonal. Specifically, ‖P P⁺ c‖ = √(∑{i=1}^m (u_iᵀ c)²). The factor σ_max/σ_min = σ₁/σ_m is the condition number κ(P). The term ‖c‖/‖P⁺c‖ equals 1/√(∑{i=1}^m (u_iᵀ c)² / σ_i²). Combining these, we obtain an inequality bounding the product AI·CI by a function that increases with κ and decreases with the alignment of c. The detailed derivation uses the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality and the fact that ∑ (u_iᵀ c)² ≤ 1. For equality, c must be a singular vector corresponding to σ₁ and also satisfy specific orthogonality conditions.

This theorem formalizes the intuitive notion that high adaptation (large nullspace) necessarily limits the ability to achieve arbitrary coupled motions, and vice versa. The condition number amplifies the trade-off when P is ill-conditioned.

3.4.4 Toward Resolution: Variable Transmission and Reconfiguration

A complete resolution of the paradox requires mechanisms that can change P during the grasp or introduce additional constraints. The port-Hamiltonian framework naturally accommodates such extensions:

· Variable Transmission: Let P(q) be configuration-dependent. Then the adaptation index becomes a local quantity AI(P(q)) = (n - rank(P(q))) / rank(P(q)), which can vary during motion. Optimal designs might have high AI during approach (for adaptation) and low AI during power grasp (for stability).
· Joint Locks: Following Wassink et al. (2010), we model joint locks as discrete reconfiguration events that temporarily increase rank(P) by locking degrees of freedom. This can be represented as switching between Dirac structures in the port-Hamiltonian formulation.
· Mode-Switching Mechanisms: Recent patents (e.g., Gosselin & Laliberté 2014) describe mechanisms that switch between coupled and adaptive modes. In our framework, these correspond to discrete changes in P at specific configurations, representable as hybrid port-Hamiltonian systems with state-triggered switching.

3.5 Theoretical Design Exploration

To illustrate the framework's utility as a conceptual design tool, we consider a theoretical design space for a 2-DOF underactuated finger (MCP and PIP joints, one actuator). The design variables are the coupling ratio k in P = [1, k]ᵀ, the spring stiffnesses K₁ and K₂ at the two joints, and a binary variable s indicating whether tendons are sheathed (opacity 0.8) or exposed (opacity 0). We define two objectives:

· Functional: Maximize coupling index CI(P, c) for a desired power grasp synergy c = [1,1]ᵀ. For a 2-DOF finger, CI(P,c) = |1+k| / √(2(1+k²)).
· Tectonic: Maximize mechanical legibility ML = TVI, where TVI = 1/(1 + s·0.8) (simplified proxy).

We explore the Pareto frontier by varying k continuously and s discretely. The trade-off is clear: higher k (near 1) gives better coupling but may require sheathing that reduces legibility; lower k gives worse coupling but allows exposed tendons. The Pareto frontier reveals that for any desired level of coupling, the best tectonic design is the one with highest TVI achievable at that coupling. This theoretical exercise demonstrates how the framework enables quantitative trade-off analysis without requiring physical implementation.

