Chapter 4: Architectural-Design Framework for Hand Representation

4.1 Spatial Grammars for Hand Movements

4.1.1 Algebraic Formalization

We define a spatial grammar G = (P, R, C) where:

· Primitives P: Each primitive is a triple (ϕ, j, θ) representing a fundamental movement. More generally, a primitive can be represented as an element of SE(3) or its Lie algebra, capturing the net motion of a segment. For example:
  · Flexion: Flex(ϕ, j) ↦ θⱼ ← ϕ with ϕ ∈ [ϕ_min, ϕ_max]
  · Extension: Ext(ϕ, j) ↦ θⱼ ← -ϕ
  · Abduction: Abd(ϕ, j) ↦ θⱼ ← ϕ (for abduction joints)
  · Adduction: Add(ϕ, j) ↦ θⱼ ← -ϕ
  · Opposition: Opp(α) ↦ sequence of thumb CMC rotations
  In the SE(3) interpretation, a flexion primitive corresponds to a one-parameter subgroup generated by the screw axis of that joint.
· Rules R: Rules are composition operations on primitives:
  · Sequence: Seq(α, β) = β ∘ α (function composition in configuration space)
  · Parallel: Par(α, β) = α × β (product in configuration space)
  · Repeat: Rep(α, n) = αⁿ (n-fold composition)
  · Conditional: Cond(cond, α, β) = α if cond true else β
· Constraints C: Constraints are inequalities on configuration variables:
  · Joint limits: θⱼ_min ≤ θⱼ ≤ θⱼ_max
  · Penetration avoidance: dist(T_f(θ_f), T_g(θ_g)) ≥ ε for f ≠ g
  · Force closure: rank(G) = 6 where G is the grasp matrix in screw coordinates

4.1.2 Generating Hand Configurations

Starting from an initial configuration θ⁽⁰⁾ (e.g., open hand), the grammar generates new configurations by applying rules. Each rule application defines a mapping r: C → C.

For example, a precision pinch might be generated as:
Par(Par(Flex(45°, MCP_index), Flex(45°, PIP_index)), Par(Flex(10°, DIP_index), Opp(thumb_to_index)))

The grammar defines a partial order on configurations, enabling hierarchical planning and description.

4.1.3 Expressiveness of the Grammar

The grammar G is capable of generating a wide range of hand configurations. In particular, because each revolute joint can be independently actuated by a primitive, and sequence and parallel rules allow any combination of joint angles, the grammar can generate all configurations that correspond to discrete combinations of primitive actions. However, since joint angles are continuous, the grammar's reachable set is a dense subset of the configuration space C (assuming primitives can be instantiated with any angle within joint limits). More formally, the grammar can generate any configuration that can be expressed as a finite composition of primitives with real parameters; this set is dense in C. Therefore, the grammar is sufficiently expressive to represent all grasp types in standard taxonomies such as Cutkosky's (1989) 16 grasps or Feix et al.'s (2016) 33 grasps, as each such grasp corresponds to a specific region in joint-angle space that can be approximated by appropriate primitive parameters and rule applications. The grammar also allows the inclusion of constraints that restrict the generated set to feasible configurations (e.g., joint limits). Thus, while we do not claim that the grammar generates every physically realizable configuration (a topological denseness claim would require proof beyond our scope), it is certainly expressive enough for design purposes.

4.1.4 Relation to Joint‑Angle Spaces

The grammar defines a mapping G: S → C from symbolic descriptions S to joint‑angle vectors. This mapping is many‑to‑one: multiple symbolic descriptions may correspond to the same joint‑angle configuration, reflecting different design interpretations. Conversely, a single symbolic description may correspond to a family of configurations parameterized by continuous parameters (e.g., flexion angles).

For theoretical analysis, we define an inverse mapping G⁻¹: C → 2^S that returns all symbolic descriptions consistent with a given configuration, using constraint satisfaction and pattern matching.

