Appendix A: Mathematical Preliminaries

A.1 Lie Groups and Lie Algebras

A Lie group is a group that is also a smooth manifold, with the property that the group operations (multiplication and inversion) are smooth maps. The Lie algebra associated with a Lie group G is the tangent space at the identity, denoted \mathfrak{g} = T_eG, equipped with a bilinear, antisymmetric bracket [\cdot,\cdot]: \mathfrak{g}\times\mathfrak{g}\to\mathfrak{g} called the Lie bracket, which satisfies the Jacobi identity.

A.1.1 The Special Orthogonal Group SO(3)

SO(3) = \{R \in \mathbb{R}^{3\times3} \mid R^T R = I,\ \det R = +1\} is the group of rotations in \mathbb{R}^3. Its Lie algebra \mathfrak{so}(3) consists of skew-symmetric matrices:

\mathfrak{so}(3) = \{\hat{\omega} \in \mathbb{R}^{3\times3} \mid \hat{\omega}^T = -\hat{\omega}\}.

Every such matrix can be written as

\hat{\omega} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & -\omega_3 & \omega_2 \\ \omega_3 & 0 & -\omega_1 \\ -\omega_2 & \omega_1 & 0 \end{bmatrix},

with \omega = (\omega_1,\omega_2,\omega_3) \in \mathbb{R}^3. The map \omega \mapsto \hat{\omega} is an isomorphism between \mathbb{R}^3 and \mathfrak{so}(3). The Lie bracket in \mathfrak{so}(3) corresponds to the cross product: [\hat{\omega}_1, \hat{\omega}_2] = \widehat{\omega_1 \times \omega_2}.

The exponential map \exp: \mathfrak{so}(3) \to SO(3) is given by Rodrigues' formula:

\exp(\hat{\omega}) = I + \frac{\sin\|\omega\|}{\|\omega\|} \hat{\omega} + \frac{1-\cos\|\omega\|}{\|\omega\|^2} \hat{\omega}^2,

with the convention that for \|\omega\| = 0, \exp(0) = I.

A.1.2 The Special Euclidean Group SE(3)

SE(3) = \{(R,p) \mid R \in SO(3), p \in \mathbb{R}^3\} is the group of rigid motions (rotations and translations). Group multiplication:

(R_1, p_1) \cdot (R_2, p_2) = (R_1R_2, R_1p_2 + p_1).

A convenient representation uses 4\times4 homogeneous matrices:

T = \begin{bmatrix} R & p \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix} \in \mathbb{R}^{4\times4}.

Then multiplication corresponds to matrix multiplication.

The Lie algebra \mathfrak{se}(3) consists of matrices of the form

\hat{\xi} = \begin{bmatrix} \hat{\omega} & v \\ 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix} \in \mathbb{R}^{4\times4},

with \hat{\omega} \in \mathfrak{so}(3), v \in \mathbb{R}^3. The twist coordinates are \xi = (v, \omega) \in \mathbb{R}^6.

The exponential map \exp: \mathfrak{se}(3) \to SE(3) can be computed as:

\exp(\hat{\xi}) = \begin{bmatrix} \exp(\hat{\omega}) & \frac{1}{\|\omega\|^2}\big((I - \exp(\hat{\omega}))(\omega\times v) + \omega\omega^T v \|\omega\| \big) \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix},

with the understanding that when \omega = 0 (pure translation), \exp(\hat{\xi}) = \begin{bmatrix} I & v \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}.

A.1.3 Adjoint Representation

For a Lie group G, the adjoint representation \Ad_g: \mathfrak{g} \to \mathfrak{g} is the differential of conjugation at the identity:

\Ad_g(\xi) = \frac{d}{dt}\big(g \exp(t\xi) g^{-1}\big)\big|_{t=0}.

For SE(3), if g = (R,p) and \xi = (v,\omega), then

\Ad_g(\xi) = (R v + p \times (R\omega),\, R\omega).

In matrix form (using homogeneous coordinates),

\Ad_g = \begin{bmatrix} R & \hat{p}R \\ 0 & R \end{bmatrix},

where \hat{p} is the skew-symmetric matrix of p.

The Lie algebra adjoint map \ad_\xi: \mathfrak{g} \to \mathfrak{g} is defined by \ad_\xi(\eta) = [\xi, \eta]. For \mathfrak{se}(3),

\ad_\xi = \begin{bmatrix} \hat{\omega} & \hat{v} \\ 0 & \hat{\omega} \end{bmatrix},

where \hat{v} is the skew-symmetric matrix of v.

A.2 Screw Theory

A screw is a geometric entity consisting of a line in space (the screw axis) and a scalar called the pitch. A twist \xi = (v,\omega) represents the instantaneous velocity of a rigid body. If \omega \neq 0, the screw axis is the line through the point

q = \frac{\omega \times v}{\|\omega\|^2}

in the direction \omega, and the pitch is

h = \frac{\omega \cdot v}{\|\omega\|^2}.

If \omega = 0 (pure translation), the screw axis is the line through the origin in the direction v, and the pitch is infinite (or conventionally, a translational screw).

The screw coordinates of a joint are often given as a unit twist (normalized so that \|\omega\| = 1 for revolute joints, or \|v\| = 1 for prismatic joints). For a revolute joint with axis direction \omega and a point q on the axis, the screw coordinates are

\mathcal{S} = \begin{bmatrix} -\omega \times q \\ \omega \end{bmatrix}.

For a prismatic joint with direction v,

\mathcal{S} = \begin{bmatrix} v \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}.

A.3 Product of Exponentials Formula

For an open kinematic chain with n joints, let the screw axis for joint i be \mathcal{S}_i (expressed in the base frame when the manipulator is at the home configuration). Let \theta_i be the joint displacement. Then the forward kinematics relative to a home configuration M \in SE(3) is

T(\theta) = e^{[\mathcal{S}_1]\theta_1} e^{[\mathcal{S}_2]\theta_2} \cdots e^{[\mathcal{S}_n]\theta_n} M,

where [\mathcal{S}_i] is the 4\times4 matrix representation of the twist.

If the screw axes are expressed in the end-effector frame (body frame), the formula becomes

T(\theta) = M e^{[\mathcal{B}_1]\theta_1} e^{[\mathcal{B}_2]\theta_2} \cdots e^{[\mathcal{B}_n]\theta_n},

with \mathcal{B}_i being the screw axis in the end-effector frame.

A.4 Port-Hamiltonian Systems

A port-Hamiltonian system on a manifold \mathcal{X} with Hamiltonian H: \mathcal{X} \to \mathbb{R} is given by

\dot{x} = [J(x) - R(x)] \frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x) + g(x) u,

y = g(x)^T \frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x),

where:

· J(x) is a skew-symmetric matrix (interconnection structure),
· R(x) is a symmetric positive semi-definite matrix (dissipation),
· g(x) is the input matrix,
· (u, y) are power-conjugate port variables (i.e., u^T y is the power supplied).

The Hamiltonian H represents the total stored energy. The structure matrix J(x) defines the energy-conserving interconnection between energy storage elements. Dissipation is modeled by R(x). The port variables couple the system to the environment.

For mechanical systems with configuration q and momentum p, the Hamiltonian is often H(q,p) = \frac{1}{2} p^T M^{-1}(q) p + V(q), where M(q) is the mass matrix and V(q) is potential energy. The natural interconnection structure for such systems is

J = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & I \\ -I & 0 \end{bmatrix},

which corresponds to the canonical symplectic structure.

A.5 Tendon-Driven Finger Modeling

For a tendon-driven finger with n joints and m tendons, let \theta \in \mathbb{R}^n be joint angles, and let \ell \in \mathbb{R}^m be tendon displacements (positive for pulling). The kinematics of tendon routing is described by the coupling matrix P(\theta) \in \mathbb{R}^{m\times n} such that

\Delta \ell = P(\theta) \Delta \theta.

By the principle of virtual work, the relationship between tendon tensions f \in \mathbb{R}^m and joint torques \tau \in \mathbb{R}^n is

\tau = P(\theta)^T f.

The matrix P can be configuration-dependent if the moment arms change with joint angles (e.g., due to tendon wrapping or variable-radius pulleys). The rank of P determines the degree of actuation: if \rank(P) = r, then the finger has r independent actuated directions, and n-r directions are underactuated (passive).

A.6 Singular Value Decomposition and Condition Number

For a matrix P \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times m} with rank r, the singular value decomposition (SVD) is

P = U \Sigma V^T,

where U \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times n}, V \in \mathbb{R}^{m\times m} are orthogonal, and \Sigma \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times m} has diagonal entries \sigma_1 \geq \sigma_2 \geq \cdots \geq \sigma_r > 0 and zeros elsewhere. The singular values \sigma_i represent the gain of the matrix along the corresponding input directions.

The condition number \kappa(P) is defined as

\kappa(P) = \frac{\sigma_{\max}}{\sigma_{\min}} = \frac{\sigma_1}{\sigma_r}.

A high condition number indicates that the matrix is ill-conditioned: small changes in input (tendon displacements) can lead to large variations in output (joint torques) depending on direction.

A.7 Grasp Matrix and Force Closure

When a hand grasps an object, contact forces f_c at k contacts relate to the resultant wrench w on the object via the grasp matrix G:

w = G f_c.

For a grasp with hard-finger contacts (no friction), G maps normal forces to wrenches. For frictional contacts, the grasp matrix includes tangential components. A grasp is said to achieve force closure if the set of wrenches that can be generated by contact forces within the friction cone spans the entire \mathbb{R}^6 space of wrenches. Mathematically, force closure is equivalent to \rank(G) = 6 and the existence of strictly positive internal forces.

In screw theory, the grasp matrix can be constructed from the contact locations and the friction cone approximations. For a thorough treatment, see Murray, Li, and Sastry (1994).

