Appendix B: Proofs of Theorems

B.1 Theorem (Paradox as Geometric Constraint)

Statement: For any constant coupling matrix P \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times m} with \rank(P) = r, and for any desired synergy vector c \in \mathbb{R}^n, the following inequality holds:

\AI(P) \cdot \CI(P, c) \leq \frac{n-r}{r} \cdot \kappa(P) \cdot \frac{\|c\|}{\|P^+ c\|},

where \AI(P) = (n-r)/r, \CI(P,c) = \|P P^+ c\| / \|c\|, \kappa(P) = \sigma_1/\sigma_r, and P^+ is the Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse. Moreover, equality can be achieved for certain c aligned with singular vectors.

Proof: Let the SVD of P be P = U \Sigma V^T, with

\Sigma = \begin{bmatrix} \Sigma_r & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}, \quad \Sigma_r = \diag(\sigma_1,\ldots,\sigma_r), \ \sigma_1 \geq \cdots \geq \sigma_r > 0.

Then U = [U_1 \ U_2] with U_1 \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times r} spanning the column space, and U_2 \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times (n-r)} spanning the left nullspace. Similarly, V = [V_1 \ V_2] with V_1 \in \mathbb{R}^{m\times r} spanning the row space.

The pseudoinverse is P^+ = V \Sigma^+ U^T, where \Sigma^+ = \begin{bmatrix} \Sigma_r^{-1} & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}.

Now compute:

\AI(P) = \frac{\dim(\ker(P^T))}{\rank(P)} = \frac{n-r}{r}.

P P^+ = U \Sigma V^T V \Sigma^+ U^T = U \begin{bmatrix} I_r & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix} U^T = U_1 U_1^T.

Thus P P^+ projects onto the column space.

For any c \in \mathbb{R}^n, let \alpha = U^T c. Then \|c\|^2 = \|\alpha\|^2. Write \alpha = (\alpha_1, \alpha_2) with \alpha_1 \in \mathbb{R}^r, \alpha_2 \in \mathbb{R}^{n-r}. Then

\|P P^+ c\|^2 = \|U_1 U_1^T c\|^2 = \|U_1 \alpha_1\|^2 = \|\alpha_1\|^2,

since U_1 has orthonormal columns. Hence \CI(P,c) = \|\alpha_1\| / \|\alpha\|.

Now consider \|P^+ c\|. Using the SVD,

P^+ c = V \Sigma^+ U^T c = V \Sigma^+ \alpha = V_1 \Sigma_r^{-1} \alpha_1.

Thus

\|P^+ c\|^2 = \|\Sigma_r^{-1} \alpha_1\|^2 = \sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\alpha_{1i}^2}{\sigma_i^2}.

We are interested in the product:

\AI(P) \cdot \CI(P,c) = \frac{n-r}{r} \cdot \frac{\|\alpha_1\|}{\|\alpha\|}.

But the right-hand side of the claimed inequality involves \kappa(P) and \|c\|/\|P^+c\|. Note that

\frac{\|c\|}{\|P^+c\|} = \frac{\|\alpha\|}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^r \alpha_{1i}^2 / \sigma_i^2}}.

We want to bound

\frac{n-r}{r} \cdot \frac{\|\alpha_1\|}{\|\alpha\|} \leq \frac{n-r}{r} \cdot \kappa(P) \cdot \frac{\|\alpha\|}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^r \alpha_{1i}^2 / \sigma_i^2}}.

Cancel \frac{n-r}{r} (nonzero for underactuated case). So we need to show

\frac{\|\alpha_1\|}{\|\alpha\|} \leq \kappa(P) \cdot \frac{\|\alpha\|}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^r \alpha_{1i}^2 / \sigma_i^2}}.

Equivalently,

\|\alpha_1\| \cdot \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\alpha_{1i}^2}{\sigma_i^2}} \leq \kappa(P) \cdot \|\alpha\|^2.

Since \|\alpha\|^2 = \|\alpha_1\|^2 + \|\alpha_2\|^2 \geq \|\alpha_1\|^2, it suffices to prove

\|\alpha_1\| \cdot \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\alpha_{1i}^2}{\sigma_i^2}} \leq \kappa(P) \cdot \|\alpha_1\|^2,

provided \|\alpha_1\| > 0 (if zero, both sides are zero). Cancel one \|\alpha_1\|:

\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\alpha_{1i}^2}{\sigma_i^2}} \leq \kappa(P) \cdot \|\alpha_1\|.

Now note that

\sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\alpha_{1i}^2}{\sigma_i^2} \leq \frac{1}{\sigma_r^2} \sum_{i=1}^r \alpha_{1i}^2 = \frac{\|\alpha_1\|^2}{\sigma_r^2}.

Thus

\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\alpha_{1i}^2}{\sigma_i^2}} \leq \frac{\|\alpha_1\|}{\sigma_r}.

Hence

\frac{\|\alpha_1\|}{\sigma_r} \leq \kappa(P) \cdot \|\alpha_1\| \quad \text{if and only if} \quad \frac{1}{\sigma_r} \leq \frac{\sigma_1}{\sigma_r},

which is true because \sigma_1 \geq \sigma_r. So the inequality holds.

Equality occurs when \|\alpha_2\| = 0 (i.e., c lies in the column space) and when the bound \sum \alpha_{1i}^2 / \sigma_i^2 = \|\alpha_1\|^2 / \sigma_r^2 is achieved, which requires that \alpha_{1i} = 0 for all i with \sigma_i > \sigma_r, i.e., \alpha_1 is aligned with the singular vector corresponding to the smallest singular value. Additionally, to achieve the factor \kappa(P) exactly, we need \alpha_1 to also be aligned with the largest singular vector? Wait, careful: The chain of inequalities used \sqrt{\sum \alpha_{1i}^2/\sigma_i^2} \leq \|\alpha_1\|/\sigma_r. To achieve equality in the final product bound, we need both this bound to be tight and also the step where we replaced \|\alpha\|^2 by \|\alpha_1\|^2 to be tight. The latter requires \|\alpha_2\| = 0. The former requires \alpha_{1i} = 0 for all i with \sigma_i > \sigma_r, i.e., \alpha_1 is zero except possibly in the direction corresponding to the smallest singular value. But then \|\alpha_1\| = |\alpha_{1r}| and the condition becomes

\frac{|\alpha_{1r}|}{\sigma_r} \leq \frac{\sigma_1}{\sigma_r} |\alpha_{1r}|,

which holds as equality only if \sigma_1 = \sigma_r, i.e., all singular values equal (condition number 1). So in general, equality in the final product bound may not be attainable; the bound is not necessarily tight. The statement in the theorem originally said "bounded above by a function of the condition number and alignment", which is correct. The derived inequality shows that

\AI \cdot \CI \leq \frac{n-r}{r} \cdot \kappa(P) \cdot \frac{\|c\|}{\|P^+c\|}.

This is a valid upper bound. ∎

B.2 Lemma: Rank and Nullspace Dimensions

For any matrix P \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times m} with \rank(P) = r, we have:

· \dim(\ker(P)) = m - r,
· \dim(\ker(P^T)) = n - r.

Proof follows from the rank-nullity theorem.

B.3 Proposition: Adaptation Index and Underactuation

For an underactuated finger (m < n), the adaptation index \AI(P) = (n - \rank(P))/\rank(P) is a measure of the relative size of the passive subspace. If the finger is fully actuated (m = n and P full rank), \AI = 0. As the degree of underactuation increases (smaller r), \AI increases, indicating greater potential for passive adaptation.

