Appendix C: Extended Pattern Language Documentation

C.1 Pattern Template

Each pattern is documented using the following template:

· Name: A concise name.
· Context: When to use this pattern.
· Problem: The design issue addressed.
· Solution: The core design principle.
· Mathematical Realization: Equations, joint ranges, coupling matrices, etc.
· Force Closure Condition: Required contact geometry and forces.
· Restraining Forces: Factors that can prevent successful implementation (e.g., friction, joint limits, tendon slack).
· Variations: Alternative implementations.
· Related Patterns: Links to other patterns at different scales.

C.2 Finger-Scale Patterns (Detailed)

F1: Adaptive Enclosure

· Context: Grasping objects of unknown shape and size; when the hand must conform to the object without active control of each joint.
· Problem: Rigidly coupled fingers cannot adapt to object contours, leading to unstable grasps or damage.
· Solution: Use underactuation with a single actuator driving multiple joints through a compliant transmission. Joints stop upon contact, allowing the remaining joints to continue closing.
· Mathematical Realization: Coupling matrix P with rank 1, e.g., P = [1, k_2, k_3, \dots]^T where k_i are coupling ratios. Nullspace dimension n-1 (maximum adaptation). Joint springs with stiffness K_i determine contact forces. AI high.
· Force Closure Condition: After adaptation, the finger must exert sufficient normal forces to achieve force closure; requires that contact normals lie within friction cones.
· Restraining Forces: Friction in tendons can prevent full adaptation; joint limits may stop motion prematurely.
· Variations: Different coupling ratios (e.g., k_i decreasing distally) to promote sequential contact.
· Related Patterns: F3 (Sequential Flexion) is a specific instance.

F2: Precision Point

· Context: Manipulating small objects where fingertip accuracy is paramount.
· Problem: Distributed contact across multiple phalanges reduces precision.
· Solution: Design coupling so that distal joints move preferentially, ensuring fingertip contact first.
· Mathematical Realization: P with high distal coupling, e.g., P = [1, 0.2, 0.05]^T for a 3-joint finger. Distal joint stiffness relatively high.
· Force Closure Condition: Single-point contact must be within friction cone; grasp matrix rank may be less than 6, requiring careful force control.
· Restraining Forces: Tendon stretch can reduce precision; backlash in joints.
· Variations: Can be combined with abduction for lateral precision.
· Related Patterns: H2 (Precision Pinch) at hand scale.

F3: Sequential Flexion

· Context: Objects with protrusions or varying depths; ensuring that proximal joints stop first.
· Problem: If all joints stop simultaneously, the finger may not conform to complex shapes.
· Solution: Design increasing stiffness from proximal to distal joints, or use mechanical limits that engage sequentially.
· Mathematical Realization: K_1 < K_2 < K_3 for a three-joint finger; coupling matrix may be uniform or decreasing gains.
· Force Closure Condition: After sequential stop, final configuration should envelop object.
· Restraining Forces: Friction can prevent proper sequencing if it causes joint stiction.
· Variations: Use of mechanical stops at specific angles.
· Related Patterns: F1 (Adaptive Enclosure) is a generalization.

F4: Coupled Flexion

· Context: Power grasps where speed and simultaneous closure are essential.
· Problem: Sequential motion slows down grasp formation.
· Solution: High coupling ratios so all joints move together; minimal compliance.
· Mathematical Realization: P = [1,1,1]^T (for 3 joints), high joint stiffness.
· Force Closure Condition: Requires object shape to be compatible with fixed coupling; otherwise grasp may be unstable.
· Restraining Forces: Friction less critical; but if object is irregular, may not adapt.
· Variations: Could incorporate mode-switching to transition from coupled to adaptive.
· Related Patterns: H1 (Power Grasp).

F5: Abduction/Adduction

· Context: Lateral grasping or spreading fingers for wide objects.
· Problem: Pure flexion cannot handle lateral forces or adjust finger spacing.
· Solution: Provide independent abduction DOF with dedicated actuation or coupling.
· Mathematical Realization: Full-rank P for the abduction subspace; often a separate actuator.
· Force Closure Condition: Abduction/adduction must be locked or controlled to maintain grasp.
· Restraining Forces: Cross-coupling with flexion can cause unwanted motions.
· Variations: Can be underactuated with springs returning to neutral.
· Related Patterns: H7 (Spherical Grasp) requires abduction.

C.3 Hand-Scale Patterns (Detailed)

H1: Power Grasp

· Context: Large objects, high force requirements (e.g., hammer, bottle).
· Problem: Need maximum contact and force transmission.
· Solution: All fingers flex to enclose object, thumb opposes from opposite side.
· Mathematical Realization: \theta_{\text{MCP}} \in [70^\circ,90^\circ], \theta_{\text{PIP}} \in [80^\circ,100^\circ], \theta_{\text{DIP}} follows natural coupling. Thumb CMC in opposition.
· Force Closure Condition: Force closure achieved if contact normals converge and friction sufficient.
· Restraining Forces: Slippage due to low friction; object shape may prevent full enclosure.
· Variations: Cylindrical vs. spherical power grasp.
· Related Patterns: F4 (Coupled Flexion) at finger scale.

H2: Precision Pinch

· Context: Small objects requiring fine control (e.g., needle, coin).
· Problem: Need high accuracy, minimal contact area.
· Solution: Thumb opposes index fingertip; other fingers may curl out of the way.
· Mathematical Realization: Index: \theta_{\text{MCP}} \approx 45^\circ, \theta_{\text{PIP}} \approx 45^\circ, \theta_{\text{DIP}} \approx 10^\circ. Thumb: CMC flexed, MCP and IP slightly flexed to oppose.
· Force Closure Condition: Force closure not strictly required; stability maintained by precise force control.
· Restraining Forces: Tendon slack, backlash.
· Variations: Tip pinch (only distal contacts), lateral pinch (thumb opposes side of index).
· Related Patterns: F2 (Precision Point).

H3: Lateral Pinch

· Context: Thin objects like keys, cards, paper.
· Problem: Conventional pinch may not provide enough lateral stability.
· Solution: Index finger extended, thumb flexes to press object against lateral side of index.
· Mathematical Realization: Index MCP ≈ 20°, PIP ≈ 10°, DIP ≈ 5°. Thumb adducted and flexed.
· Force Closure Condition: Requires high friction; often used for precision rather than force closure.
· Restraining Forces: Object may slip if thumb pressure insufficient.
· Variations: Can use middle finger for additional support.
· Related Patterns: F5 (Abduction/Adduction) may be involved.

H4: Three-Jaw Chuck

· Context: Spherical objects, moderate precision (e.g., ball, apple).
· Problem: Two fingers insufficient for stable grasp of sphere.
· Solution: Thumb, index, and middle form a tripod around object.
· Mathematical Realization: Fingertip positions approximately equally spaced on a circle; joint angles adjusted to bring tips to contact.
· Force Closure Condition: Force closure possible with three frictional contacts.
· Restraining Forces: Object may roll if contacts not symmetric.
· Variations: Can be used with soft fingertips for conformability.
· Related Patterns: F1 (Adaptive Enclosure) at finger scale.

H5: Hook Grasp

· Context: Carrying objects with handles (e.g., suitcase, bucket).
· Problem: Fingers must resist gravity without requiring thumb engagement.
· Solution: Fingers flex to form a hook, thumb may remain unengaged.
· Mathematical Realization: \theta_{\text{MCP}},\theta_{\text{PIP}} \in [85^\circ,95^\circ], \theta_{\text{DIP}} free (often follows coupling). Wrist straight or slightly extended.
· Force Closure Condition: Not force closure; relies on form closure (handle prevents fingers from opening).
· Restraining Forces: Slipping if handle smooth.
· Variations: Can use multiple fingers.
· Related Patterns: F4 (Coupled Flexion) may be used.

H6: Cylindrical Grasp

· Context: Cylindrical objects like drinking glass, tool handle.
· Problem: Need to wrap around cylinder with palm contact.
· Solution: Full finger flexion with palm contact; thumb either opposes or aligns along cylinder.
· Mathematical Realization: \theta_{\text{MCP}} \approx \theta_{\text{PIP}} \approx \theta_{\text{DIP}} \approx 90^\circ for fingers; thumb CMC in opposition or adduction depending on orientation.
· Force Closure Condition: Force closure if thumb opposes and friction sufficient.
· Restraining Forces: Object may rotate if grip too loose.
· Variations: Different diameters require scaling of joint angles.
· Related Patterns: H1 (Power Grasp) is similar but more general.

H7: Spherical Grasp

· Context: Grasping balls or rounded objects.
· Problem: Fingers must spread and flex to conform to curvature.
· Solution: Abduction combined with graded flexion; fingertips converge.
· Mathematical Realization: \theta_{\text{abd}} > 0, increasing for fingers farther from thumb; \theta_{\text{flex}} varies with finger length to bring tips to surface.
· Force Closure Condition: Force closure with three or more contacts.
· Restraining Forces: Object may slip if curvature mismatched.
· Variations: Can be underactuated to adapt automatically.
· Related Patterns: H4 (Three-Jaw Chuck) is a subset.

H8: Tip Pinch

· Context: Very small objects (e.g., needle, pin).
· Problem: Need maximum precision, minimal contact area.
· Solution: Only fingertips contact, with minimal joint flexion.
· Mathematical Realization: \theta_{\text{MCP}} \approx 10^\circ, \theta_{\text{PIP}} \approx 10^\circ, \theta_{\text{DIP}} \approx 0^\circ. Thumb similarly slightly flexed.
· Force Closure Condition: Not force closure; requires careful force control.
· Restraining Forces: Tremor or backlash.
· Variations: Can involve two or three fingers.
· Related Patterns: H2 (Precision Pinch) with more extreme angles.

C.4 Task-Scale Patterns (Detailed)

T1: Preshape Configuration

· Context: During approach to an object, the hand must adopt a shape that anticipates the final grasp.
· Problem: Starting from an arbitrary configuration, the hand needs to transition smoothly to the grasp.
· Solution: Use a preshape that is a scaled or offset version of the target grasp, opening the hand wider than the object.
· Mathematical Realization: \theta_{\text{preshape}} = \alpha \theta_{\text{grasp}} + \beta, with \alpha \approx 1.2 and \beta chosen to open joints.
· Force Closure Condition: Not applicable during approach.
· Restraining Forces: Joint limits may prevent full opening.
· Variations: Different preshapes for different grasp families.
· Related Patterns: All hand-scale patterns have associated preshapes.

T2: In-Hand Manipulation

· Context: Repositioning an object within the grasp without releasing it.
· Problem: Object must move relative to the palm while maintaining contact.
· Solution: Sequential finger motions that shift the object while maintaining force closure.
· Mathematical Realization: Time-varying \theta(t) such that contact points move appropriately and grasp matrix remains full rank.
· Force Closure Condition: Must be maintained throughout motion.
· Restraining Forces: Friction limits, object slippage.
· Variations: Rolling, sliding, or finger gaiting.
· Related Patterns: Involves multiple finger-scale patterns over time.

T3: Object Transfer

· Context: Handing an object from one hand to another or to a robot.
· Problem: Must release at the right time and coordinate with receiving hand.
· Solution: Synchronized release and acquisition, with both hands maintaining force closure until transfer complete.
· Mathematical Realization: Two-hand configuration space with synchronization constraints.
· Force Closure Condition: Must be maintained in at least one hand at all times.
· Restraining Forces: Timing errors, misalignment.
· Variations: Can involve regrasping.
· Related Patterns: Involves T2 and various hand-scale patterns.

T4: Tool Use

· Context: Using a tool (e.g., hammer, screwdriver) where grasp must transmit forces and moments.
· Problem: Grasp must be stable under dynamic loads and allow tool manipulation.
· Solution: Grasp that provides appropriate force transmission, often a power grasp or specialized precision grasp.
· Mathematical Realization: Grasp configuration optimized for tool dynamics, e.g., align hand with tool axis.
· Force Closure Condition: Required to resist task forces.
· Restraining Forces: Tool shape may limit feasible grasps.
· Variations: Task-specific optimizations.
· Related Patterns: H1 (Power Grasp) or H2 (Precision Pinch) modified.

T5: Precision-to-Power Transition

· Context: Tasks that start with precision (e.g., picking up a pen) and transition to power (e.g., writing).
· Problem: Need to change grasp type smoothly without dropping object.
· Solution: Trajectory in configuration space that interpolates between precision and power configurations while maintaining contact.
· Mathematical Realization: Interpolated path \theta(t) = (1-\lambda(t))\theta_{\text{precision}} + \lambda(t)\theta_{\text{power}}, with \lambda(t) from 0 to 1, satisfying force closure at all times.
· Force Closure Condition: Must be maintained throughout.
· Restraining Forces: Intermediate configurations may be unstable.
· Variations: Can involve finger repositioning.
· Related Patterns: T2 (In-Hand Manipulation) is similar but more general.

